<link rel="stylesheet" href="/public/css/assets-demo.css">

<section>
  <h1>Assets demo</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Loading this one page pulls in <strong>several local assets</strong> — two
    stylesheets, two scripts, and four images. Each is a separate HTTP request,
    fired close together over the same kept-alive TCP connection(s).
  </p>

  <div class="tile-grid">
    <img src="/public/img/sample.png" alt="sample">
    <img src="/public/img/tile-a.png" alt="tile a">
    <img src="/public/img/tile-b.png" alt="tile b">
    <img src="/public/img/tile-c.png" alt="tile c">
  </div>

  <p class="asset-note">Images referenced by this page:
    <strong id="asset-count">…</strong></p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Capture this</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Reload with your capture running, then filter
      <code>http.request.uri contains "/public/"</code> to list every asset request.</li>
    <li>See many GETs in quick succession — practice narrowing:
      <code>http.request.uri contains ".png"</code>,
      <code>http.request.uri contains ".css"</code>.</li>
    <li>Watch HTTP keep-alive: multiple requests reuse the same TCP stream
      (follow <code>tcp.stream eq &lt;n&gt;</code>) instead of a new handshake each time.</li>
    <li>Spot <code>304 Not Modified</code> on a second reload — the browser
      revalidates cached assets.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<script src="/public/js/assets-demo.js"></script>
